topics.content:
Theory:
C++ is a high-performance, object-oriented programming language used in operating systems, games, database engines, and real-time systems.

Example:
#include <iostream>
using namespace std;
int main() {
    cout << "Hello, C++";
    return 0;
}

Theory:
Variables store data. Common data types: int, float, double, char, bool, string.

Example:
int age = 20;
float price = 50.5;
char grade = 'A';
bool isPass = true;

Theory:
Conditional statements control decision making: if, else if, else.

Example:
int marks = 85;
if (marks >= 90) cout << "A";
else if (marks >= 80) cout << "B";
else cout << "C";

Theory:
Loops repeat code: for, while, do-while.

Example:
for (int i = 1; i <= 5; i++) {
    cout << i << " ";
}

Theory:
Functions are reusable blocks of code with return type, name, and parameters.

Example:
int add(int a, int b) {
    return a + b;
}
int main() {
    cout << add(5, 3);
}

Theory:
Arrays store multiple values of the same type in contiguous memory.

Example:
int arr[3] = {1, 2, 3};
for (int i = 0; i < 3; i++) cout << arr[i] << " ";

Theory:
Strings are used to store text. Handled using <string>.

Example:
string name = "Alice";
cout << name;

Theory:
Pointers store memory addresses of variables.

Example:
int x = 10;
int* p = &x;
cout << *p;

Theory:
Structures group different data types.

Example:
struct Student {
  string name;
  int age;
};
Student s = {"Raj", 19};
cout << s.name;

Theory:
OOP focuses on classes, objects, abstraction, encapsulation, inheritance, polymorphism.

Example:
class Car {
public:
  void start() { cout << "Car started"; }
};
int main() { Car c; c.start(); }

Theory:
Classes are blueprints. Objects are instances.

Example:
class Student {
public:
  string name;
};
Student s; s.name = "Aman";

Theory:
Constructors initialize objects; destructors clean resources.

Example:
class A {
public:
  A() { cout << "Created"; }
  ~A() { cout << "Destroyed"; }
};

Theory:
One class derives features from another.

Example:
class A { public: void hello() { cout << "Hello"; } };
class B: public A {};
B obj; obj.hello();

Theory:
Same function behaves differently: compile-time (overloading) and runtime (overriding).

Example:
class A { public: virtual void show() { cout << "A"; } };
class B: public A { public: void show() { cout << "B"; } };

Theory:
Wrapping data and functions together using private and public.

Example:
class Bank {
private: int balance;
public:
  void setBal(int b){ balance=b; }
  int getBal(){ return balance; }
};

Theory:
Used to read/write files using fstream.

Example:
ofstream file("data.txt");
file << "Hello";
file.close();

Theory:
Handle runtime errors using try, catch.

Example:
try {
  throw 10;
} catch(int x) {
  cout << "Error";
}

Theory:
STL provides powerful data structures: vector, map, set.

Example:
vector<int> v = {1,2,3};
for(int x: v) cout << x;
